<F P=100> INTER-AMERICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   OAS Meeting Views Haiti Sanctions, Other Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    OAS Meeting Views Haiti Sanctions, Other Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Amorim on Plans for Americas Summit </H4>

<F P=102> PY1006030394 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2222 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY1006030394 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belem do Para, 9 Jun (EFE) -- Brazilian Foreign 
Minister Celso Amorim today revealed that one of the proposals 
Brazil has made for the so-called Summit of the Americas is the 
creation of a special fund to finance integration processes in 
the continent. 
  Brazil believes that one way to prevent the presidential 
summit organized by U.S. President Bill Clinton from ending in 
another declaration of principles would be to propose concrete 
projects for action and promotion of hemispheric integration, 
Amorim said. 
  One of the projects, Amorim said, could be the creation of a 
specific fund within the Inter-American Development Bank (IDB) 
to help finance economic integration processes in the continent. 
  "Integration processes are essential for our country, and it 
is important to have the resources with which to carry them 
out," Amorim said during a news conference he gave on the 
occasion of the 24th OAS General Assembly, which has been taking 
place since 6 June in Belem do Para, northern Brazil. 
  According to Amorim, who mentioned this proposal to Strobe 
Talbott, U.S. under secretary of state, during a meeting they 
held on 6 June, the IDB was created precisely as an instrument 
of support for Latin American integration. 
  The resources from this fund could help the integration 
processes that have been developing in the past few years, such 
as the Common Market of the South (Mercosur), the Andean Pact, 
the Group of Three, and the Amazon Integration Treaty, among 
others. 
  Another proposal that will be made by Brazil for the Summit 
of the Americas, which will be held from 9 to 10 December in 
Miami, Florida, is to create mechanisms for financial and 
technical cooperation in the field of human rights defense. 
  Human rights conditions could improve with financial and 
technical cooperation agreements to improve the living 
conditions of prison inmates and strengthen the judicial system, 
Celso Amorim said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

