<F P=100> INTER-AMERICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   OAS Meeting Views Haiti Sanctions, Other Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    OAS Meeting Views Haiti Sanctions, Other Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Uruguay's Abreu on Chile's Mercosur Entry </H4>

<F P=102> PY0906151494 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2021 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY0906151494 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Montevideo, 8 Jun (EFE) -- Today, Uruguayan Foreign 
Minister Sergio Abreu said the Chilean proposal to establish, 
along with the Common Market of the South (Mercosur), a free 
trade zone "needs to ripen." The minister said he hopes this 
proposal "will not harm the trade benefits established for the 
signatory countries of the Asuncion Treaty," which in March 1991 
gave rise to Mercosur -- comprising Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay, 
and Uruguay. 
  While in Belem do Para (Brazil), where he is participating 
in 
the OAS General Assembly, Abreu told the Montevideo newspaper EL 
OBSERVADOR ECONOMICO that the Chilean proposal to join Mercosur 
within a free trade zone has in principle been well received by 
the Uruguayan Government. 
  Chilean Foreign Minister Carlos Figueroa announced on 6 June 
in Belem do Para that, within 10 years, his country will 
establish a free trade zone with Mercosur. Today, he formalized 
the proposal in a document he presented in Buenos Aires to 
Argentine Foreign Minister Guido Di Tella, the current Mercosur 
council president. 
  Abreu stressed: "The Chilean proposal needs to ripen because 
it only expresses a political will. A concrete proposal is 
required on the deadlines and the scope of the association 
sought by the government of President Eduardo Frei." 
  The Chilean announcement was well received from a political 
viewpoint because it is a step forward in the regional economic 
integration. It is necessary to hear the proposal's technical 
aspects before giving an official response. 
  Abreu admitted that any proposed "violation" of the common 
external tariff system, which the four Mercosur partners will 
strenuously attempt to establish next month, would be 
unacceptable. He added that the Uruguayan viewpoint is shared 
by Brazilian Foreign Minister Celso Amorim. 
  Uruguay considers unacceptable any trade agreement which 
enables another country to have privileged access to the 
seizable Argentine and Brazilian markets without paying the same 
common external tariff that must be borne by the two other 
Mercosur members. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

