<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Water Supply Stabilizes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Water Supply Stabilizes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL0906225394 Havana Radio Reloj Network in Spanish 1934 GMT 
9 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0906225394 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Reloj Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The administrative council in Havana Province has 
announced that the water supply has been stabilized in the 
municipalities and that 96 percent of the population is 
receiving this service. Havana Province, second only to Havana 
City Province, has a network of 470 aqueducts. 
  The largest water supply problem is in Madruga Municipality 
and conditions are slated to improve in Santa Cruz del Norte 
Municipality. Despite increased efforts over the last year, and 
the help which the agriculture sector has provided to the 
schools, the main problems are found in boarding schools, where 
54 pumps are in bad shape, with 29 of them no longer functioning 
at all. In order to alleviate this problem, Havana's school 
board established a program keyed towards installing water 
systems in those schools. 

</TEXT>

