<H3> <TI>   Senate Approves Law </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Senate Approves Law </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0906235994 Brasilia Voz do Brasil Network in Portuguese 
2200 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY0906235994 </F>
<F P=104>  Brasilia Voz do Brasil Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Luiz Augusto Mendonca from Planalto Palace] </F>
  [Text] President Itamar Franco may sign tonight the 
antitrust law, which was passed this afternoon by the Senate. 
  Shortly after the approval of the law, Senate President 
Humberto Lucena and Deputy Fabio Feldmann -- who was the 
rapporteur of the bill in the Chamber of Deputies -- came to 
Planalto Palace to meet with President Itamar Franco and with 
the justice and finance ministers. The meeting has not yet 
concluded. 
  Because the new law establishes that directors and members 
of 
the board of the Administrative Council for Economic Defense 
(CADE) must be appointed by the president of the Republic and 
confirmed by a majority vote of the national Congress, President 
Franco may issue tonight a provisional measure confirming 
incumbent CADE officials so that they may start implementing the 
new law tomorrow. 
  In case of price abuses, the law provides for fines of up to 
30 percent of the gross annual sales of large enterprises and 
preventive imprisonment for their directors and owners. A large 
enterprise is a group that controls 30 percent of the market. 

</TEXT>

