<F P=104>  Santiago Television Nacional de Chile Imagen 
Internacional </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Chilean Foreign Minister Carlos Figueroa returned to 
Santiago this afternoon from an important visit to Buenos Aires, 
where he discussed significant economic issues. The following 
is a report from the international airport in Pudahuel by Arturo 
Harlem: 
  [Begin recording] [Harlem] Good afternoon. Chilean Foreign 
Minister Figueroa stated that Chile has not set any deadlines 
for joining Mercosur [Common Market of the South]. He added, 
however, that Chile is very interested in achieving an agreement 
in this regard. 
  Upon his arrival from Brazil and Argentina, Foreign Minister 
Carlos Figueroa stressed that Chile's entrance to Mercosur will 
have a great impact at the regional level: 
  [Figueroa] As the foreign ministers have already stated, our 
entrance in Mercosur will have a great political and economic 
impact. If the negotiations are successful, it will result in 
important commercial benefits in the short term for all those 
countries encompassed in this agreement. 
  [Harlem] Figueroa also stated that the Chilean proposal had 
been warmly accepted by Mercosur countries. According to this 
proposal, Chile will be a Mercosur partner, and not a full 
member, because Chilean customs tariffs are substantially lower 
than those enforced in Mercosur countries. 
  Commenting on other issues, Foreign Minister Figueroa 
reasserted that the Chilean Government has no plans to discuss 
the landlocked issue with Bolivia. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

