<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tello Urges OECD To Assume Economic Leadership </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tello Urges OECD To Assume Economic Leadership </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0906224394 Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0906224394 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Milina Villasana from the "Early Morning" </F>
newscast] 
  [Text] Foreign Relations Secretary Manuel Tello has 
proposed on behalf of Mexico that the OECD assume international 
leadership in search of solutions to world economic problems. 
Mexico participated at the OECD meeting in Paris as the 25th 
member this organization. Tello presented to the organization's 
Council of Ministers an initiative that was backed by 
representatives from Sweden, Finland, Canada, and Spain. 
  On the last day of meetings, the Mexican foreign secretary 
asked the OECD to analyze the pertinence of institutions created 
as a result of the Cold War to prevent a duplication of efforts 
and to make operations more efficient. He said the organization 
is prepared to initiate a global analysis of the international 
economic cooperation system. 
  At the conclusion of the meeting, OECD President Jean Claude 
Baye said in a document that Mexico's membership in the OECD is 
a wonderful development. The OECD president added that OECD 
members view the beginning of a new phase of development for the 
organization and are pleased with Mexico's contribution. 
  This is the first time Mexico has participated as a full 
member since it officially joined the organization in April. 
The OECD includes the world's most industrialized countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

