<F P=100> SOUTH AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chilean Foreign Minister Views Border Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chilean Foreign Minister Views Border Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0906145094 Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS in Spanish 
2243 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY0906145094 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Buenos Aires, 8 Jun (NA) -- Chilean Foreign Minister 
Carlos Figueroa Serrano stressed on 8 June that his country "is 
not reviewing" the possibility of resorting to international 
arbitration over the Continental Glaciers issue while the treaty 
is under discussion by the two countries' Congresses. 
  The Chilean foreign minister made this remark during a news 
conference at Government House after a one-hour meeting with 
President Carlos Menem and Foreign Minister Guido Di Tella. 
  During the meeting, which he described as "cordial and very 
positive," Figueroa Serrano presented Menem with Chile's 
proposal to join Mercosur [Common Market of the South] as an 
"independent country." Mercosur is an integration process 
involving Argentina, Uruguay, Brazil, and Paraguay. 
  The visiting minister denied that during the meeting they 
reviewed aspects of a ruling the Rio de Janeiro Arbitration 
Court will have to issue within a few months on the Laguna del 
Desierto border conflict. 
  Instead the Chilean foreign minister extensively discussed 
the Continental Glaciers treaty and said his country "is not 
reviewing" the possibility of resorting to international 
arbitration. 
  Figueroa Serrano pointed out: "We have not discussed this 
issue, despite the fact that it is a formula that was included 
in the 1984 Peace and Friendship Treaty, because Chile's and 
Argentina's position is that here there is a proposed treaty 
that settles the Continental Glaciers border problem." 
  Figueroa Serrano added that this solution "seems to be fair 
and compatible with the terms of the border treaties between 
Chile and Argentina and this is under discussion by the 
Congresses." 
  Figueroa Serrano emphasized: "We do not want to consider any 
other alternative contemplated in the 1984 treaty while this 
issue is under discussion by the two Congresses." 
  Figueroa added that during his meeting with Menem, "we 
reviewed the relationship between the two countries and were 
able to confirm the excellent level of our current relations." 
  Figueroa Serrano immediately emphasized the "very close 
relationship" existing between President Carlos Menem and 
President Eduardo Frei, who will have a chance to meet again in 
mid-June during the Fourth Ibero-American Summit in Cartagena 
[de Indias in Colombia] and, subsequently, on 25 and 26 August 
during a new working visit that the Argentine president will pay 
to Santiago. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-33737 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat112_l_94001" </HT>


