<H3> <TI>   Canadians To Face Trial for Aiding Emigrants </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Canadians To Face Trial for Aiding Emigrants </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0806044794 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1740 GMT 7 Jun 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA0806044794 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 7 Jun (PL) -- Today, the Cuban Foreign 
Ministry confirmed that two Canadian citizens will stand trial 
in Cuba for participating in a group of people's attempt to 
illegally leave the country, which ended in two tragic deaths. 
  Michael Benditti and Robert Shymko arrived in Havana on a 
boat from Florida and stopped over at the "Marina Hemingway" 
naval base, claiming that they planned to continue their trip to 
Varadero Beach, 140 km from Havana. 
  Nevertheless, according to Foreign Ministry Spokesman Miguel 
Alfonso, the Canadians in fact traveled to Guanabo Beach, 
approximately 25 km from the capital, to facilitate the illegal 
departure from the country of eight people which, apparently, 
had been previously agreed upon. 
  The group's haste to leave prompted an accident on the beach 
which claimed the lives of two swimmers and caused serious 
injuries to another, he added. 
  Consequently, it has been officially announced that the two 
Canadians have been arrested and will be subjected to legal 
procedures established for such cases. 
  The spokesman explained that the foreigners have already 
been 
visited by officials from the Canadian Consulate in Cuba and 
that legal procedures against them are following their normal 
course. 

</TEXT>

