<H3> <TI>   Uruguay's Lacalle First To Arrive for Summit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Uruguay's Lacalle First To Arrive for Summit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1206030394 Madrid EFE in Spanish 0049 GMT 12 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1206030394 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Cartagena de Indias, Colombia, 11 Jun (EFE) -- 
Uruguayan President Luis Lacalle said today that the goal of 
consolidating the Ibero-American community of nations continues 
firm, "even though many presidents are about to complete their 
terms." By this statement, Lacalle was alluding to his own case 
and that of Brazilian President Itamar Franco, Colombian 
President Cesar Gaviria, Mexican President Carlos Salinas de 
Gortari, and Panamanian President Guillermo Endara. 
  The Uruguayan president was the first of the 22 chiefs of 
state and government to arrive in Cartagena de Indias to 
participate in the fourth Ibero-American summit that begins on 
Tuesday. 
  "It is a pleasure to step on Cartagena soil and to confirm 
that the objective we established for ourselves continues 
forward," Lacalle commented. He also praised "the great work of 
the government" of Cesar Gaviria who will end his term in 
August. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

