<H3> <TI>   OAS General Assembly Continues Brazil Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    OAS General Assembly Continues Brazil Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Backs Decade for Indigenous Peoples </H4>

<F P=102> PY1106020694 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1801 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY1106020694 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Belem, 9 Jun (EFE) -- Foreign ministers and 
delegates attending the 24th OAS General Assembly today approved 
a resolution benefiting indigenous groups, as it commits them to 
celebrating on this continent the International Decade of the 
World's Indigenous Peoples. 
  The resolution, which was proposed by Bolivia and sponsored 
by Mexico and Guatemala, was unanimously approved today by the 
delegations of the 34 OAS member states on the fourth and 
penultimate day of the assembly. 
  The resolution entrusts the OAS secretary general with the 
task of acting as regional coordinator for the International 
Decade of the World's Indigenous Peoples within the cooperation 
framework established with the United Nations. 
  Six months ago the UN General Assembly designated the decade 
starting on 10 December 1994 and ending in the year 2004 as the 
International Decade of the World's Indigenous Peoples. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

