<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Commander in Chief Fidel Castro Ruz has written 
Colombian President Cesar Gaviria expressing Cuba's solidarity 
and condolences following the natural disaster there at the 
beginning of the week. This was announced by Foreign Ministry 
spokesman Miguel Alfonso, who added that the letter also 
expressed the Cuban Government's willingness to send doctors and 
specialists to Colombia if needed. 
  Alfonso said the Foreign Ministry is pleased with recent 
statements by the Latin American Economic System -- SELA -- and 
the Nonaligned Movement [NAM] rejecting the 30-year-old U.S. 
Government blockade of Cuba. Alfonso pointed out that SELA's 3 
June decision marked the first time that this organization had 
made a statement against the blockade. Alfonso explained that 
the NAM statement was much stronger than on previous occasions 
in that it specifically advocated the UN General Assembly 
resolutions against the blockade. 
  Alfonso also mentioned the rallies several U.S. 
organizations 
held in Washington and other U.S. cities on 9 June in support of 
the bill to lift the U.S. blockade which legislator Charles 
Rangel presented before Congress and other U.S. political and 
federal entities. 

</TEXT>

