<F P=102>   PA1106014594 Paris AFP in Spanish 2024 GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1106014594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 10 Jun (AFP) -- Today, the Cuban Foreign 
Ministry neither confirmed nor denied a report on an agreement 
that would be signed in Havana on 13 June whereby a Mexican 
corporation would invest $1.5 billion in Cuba. This would be 
the largest foreign capital investment in the country in 35 
years. 
  According to reports from Mexico, the corporation Domos 
International would buy 49 percent of the state-owned Cuban 
Telecommunications Enterprise [Empresa Cubana de 
Telecomunicaciones, ETEC] for 1.5 billion through a document to 
be signed during Mexican President Carlos Salinas de Gortari's 
visit to Havana next Monday. 
  In Mexico City, one of Domos International's executives said 
the investment is endorsed by British corporations N.M. 
Rothschild and K.P.M.G. Peat Marwick. 
  Asked about the matter, Cuban Foreign Ministry spokesman 
Miguel Alfonso said he could neither confirm nor deny whether 
the signing of the document is included on the agenda, which has 
been prepared for the Mexican president's visit. 
  [Paris AFP in Spanish at 1620 GMT on 10 June reports that 
according to Pedro Sepulveda, Domos International's corporate 
director, the corporation will buy 49 percent of ETEC for $1.5 
billion next week. Press dispatches report the operation will 
include a seven-year plan of modernization that will cost $720 
million, and the agreement will be signed during Salinas' visit. 
The report adds that ETEC comprises all of Cuba's telephone 
services, excluding cellular telephones. The project includes 
replacing 200,000 of the system's existing 450,000 lines and 
expanding the system to one million lines and is endorsed by 
N.M. Rothschild, a leading bank in telecommunications 
advisership, and K.P.M.G. Peat Marwick, an auditor's enterprise 
that backed the feasibility studies] 

</TEXT>

