<H3> <TI>   Canadian Embassy Recommends Nationals Leave </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Canadian Embassy Recommends Nationals Leave </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1106000394 Paris AFP in Spanish 2250 GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1106000394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Port-au-Prince, 10 Jun (AFP) -- Tonight through its 
internal telecommunications network, the Canadian Embassy will 
recommend that Canadian citizens who do not have specific 
reasons for staying in the country after 25 June leave Haiti, a 
Canadian embassy spokesman told AFP. "The final decision will 
have to be made by each individual, however," the source said. 
  Today, the government of Ottawa joined the U.S. position by 
announcing that flights from Canada to Haiti will be suspended 
as of 25 June. The source added that the embassy had expressed 
a similar position twice in the past two years but that numerous 
Canadians, some of whom had been living in Haiti for 30 or 40 
years, had elected to stay. 
  According to the embassy, 2,400 Canadians, most of them 
holding double nationality, live in Haiti. These people include 
some 300 male and female religious teachers, most of whom come 
from Quebec province. 

</TEXT>

