<F P=101> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mayor-Elect Evans Calls For Cedras Resignation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mayor-Elect Evans Calls For Cedras Resignation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1006233594 Paris AFP in Spanish 2153 GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1006233594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Port-au-Prince, 10 Jun (AFP) -- Evans Paul, the 
mayor-elect of Port-au-Prince, today called for the resignation 
of General Raoul Cedras, commander in chief of the Haitian Armed 
Forces, to prevent implementation of new economic sanctions 
announced by President Bill Clinton. 
  Paul asserted that "the Governors Island Agreement continues 
to be the foundation for a solution to prevent new, very harsh 
and painful sanctions, which hurt all Haitians." He added that 
"it is vital for Gen. Cedras to recognize the need to respect 
his commitments." 
  Clinton announced a ban on commercial flights to begin on 25 
June and a ban on banking operations with Haiti. He also 
ordered the return of most of the U.S. citizens residing on the 
island. 
  Frantz Robert Monde, president of the Chamber of Deputies 
(close to the socialists), condemned the sanctions President 
Clinton implemented. He charged that it was a "racist, 
irrational, and an unprecedented decision." 
  Appalled, Monde asked: "Tell me which U.S. citizen can live 
on $50 a month." He was referring to the maximum amount 
Haitians living in the United States are authorized to send to 
their relatives in Haiti. 
  "I insist. The international community's strategy tends to 
punish those who voted for Jean Bertrand Aristide (the exiled 
president), who are the poorest," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

