<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Transportation Sector Strike Suspended 10 Days </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Transportation Sector Strike Suspended 10 Days </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1006190394 Caracas Union Radio Network in Spanish 1100 GMT 
10 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1006190394 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Union Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Union Radio News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The staggered transportation strikes were suspended 
once the government appointed a commission to mediate the 
conflict. This was reported by Simon Ladera, president of the 
Union of Independent Vehicles, who added that the union's 
intention is not to exert any type of pressure on the 
commission. Thus, there is a 10-day truce in the strike. 
Ladera asserted that the suspension of the strike is not a 
reaction to the Transportation and Communication Ministry's 
alleged threats to revoke independent vehicle licenses. The 
union leader also recommended that Interior Minister Ramon 
Escovar Salom take charge of security or, better yet, that he 
should take charge of the insecurity in the country because more 
drivers are being killed by criminals every day and the 
government is taking no steps to end the situation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

