<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Inter-American Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Brazil Backs Intensified Haiti Boycott at OAS </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Brazil Backs Intensified Haiti Boycott at OAS </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0906020194 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 8 
Jun 94 p 13 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY0906020194 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Antonio Jose Soares] </F>
  [Text] Belem -- Foreign Minister Celso Amorim said 
yesterday at the 24th OAS General Assembly that Brazil supports 
a peaceful solution to ending the military dictatorship of 
Haiti. Amorim suggested intensifying the economic boycott 
against Haiti, including the prohibition of flights: "Although 
Brazil cannot tolerate the military coup that overthrew 
President Jean-Bertrand Aristide, it recommends a peaceful 
solution in favor of democracy, and in keeping with the 
principle of nonintervention." 
  Argentina asked for an immediate military intervention in 
Haiti, arguing that it no longer believes in the positive 
effects of the sanctions against Haiti. The Brazilian foreign 
minister believes that if the boycott is intensified, the 
coupist Haitian military officers will not be able to resist for 
long: "After President Aristide, who obtained 70 percent of the 
votes, is reinstated in power, Brazil would find it advisable 
for the United Nations to send a peace force to that country to 
safeguard democracy, but not a military intervention." 
  The Brazilian foreign minister believes that firmer action 
against the Haitian coupists has not been possible so far, but 
that favorable conditions are now arising. Amorim defended the 
readmission of Cuba to the OAS, saying that the situation there 
is different from that in Haiti: "Now that the era and 
consequences of the Cold War are over, there is no reason to 
isolate Cuba given that an evolution toward freedom can now be 
observed there, even though it is not taking place at the 
desired pace. The situation in Haiti is different: Human 
rights are brazenly violated there." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

