<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Inter-American Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Brazil Signs OAS Protocol on Human Rights </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Brazil Signs OAS Protocol on Human Rights </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1006034494 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 9 
Jun 94 p 13 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY1006034494 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belem -- Brazilian Foreign Minister Celso Amorim 
last night signed a protocol whereby Brazil adheres to the OAS 
Convention on Human Rights and the Abolition of Capital 
Punishment, which was signed in Asuncion, Paraguay, in June 
1990. Brazil was the sixth country to sign the protocol, thus 
reaffirming its commitment to refrain from adopting the death 
penalty. 
  Amorim said that in addition to strengthening democracy, the 
protocol ensures peaceful coexistence among countries and 
respect for human rights. The protocol still requires approval 
by the Brazilian Congress. The protocol will not become 
mandatory until the congresses of two-thirds of the OAS member 
countries have ratified the convention. 
  Amorim said that the Brazilian Constitution states that 
capital punishment will not be applied in the country except in 
case of a declared war. He said: "Brazilian legislation is in 
line with the highest principles of respect for human life and 
rights." 
  Amorim concluded his speech by lauding OAS Secretary General 
Baena Soares, noting that his performance "will leave an 
indelible mark on the history of this hemisphere in terms of his 
success in promoting democracy and human rights." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

