<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   International Opposition to U.S. Embargo Viewed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    International Opposition to U.S. Embargo Viewed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1106004994 Havana Radio Havana Cuba in Spanish 0000 GMT 7 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1106004994 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Havana Cuba </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Commentary by Roberto Morejon from the "Evening Information </F>
Review" newscast] 
  [Text] The U.S. policy aimed at tightening the blockade 
against Cuba has recently proved that it completely lacks 
support. A large segment of the international community does 
not care that in his so-called message to the Cubans, U.S. 
President Bill Clinton vowed he would continue the economic 
boycott of Cuba. 
  President Clinton and U.S. Congressman Robert Torricelli, 
who 
is known worldwide as the author of the law that bears his name 
and reinforces the blockade, are now more isolated than ever 
before. Torricelli, wrapped in the anti-Cuban aura he loves to 
cultivate, failed in his attempt to interfere in the internal 
affairs of Mexico, a country he visited recently. During his 
stay in Mexico, the U.S. congressman certainly hoped to foster 
one of his aggressive moves against Cuba. But the attempt 
proved futile, and this author of a bill demanding political 
reforms in Mexico faced the rejection of deputies, high-ranking 
officials, and the media. 
  Mexican citizens belonging to the Go for Cuba solidarity 
group protested Torricelli's visit in front of the U.S. Embassy 
in Mexico City, where they burned a coffin and an effigy of the 
congressman and his anti-Cuban law. 
  In Mexico City, delegates attending the 20th Conference of 
the Latin American Economic System [SELA] passed a resolution 
condemning the U.S. economic, trade, and financial blockade of 
Cuba, which has been in force for more than 30 years. The SELA 
document urged the lifting of all restrictions against Cuba -- 
the effects of which it described as detrimental to the 
population -- and it demanded the suspension of unilateral 
actions that are not in keeping with the current international 
economic and political environment. 
  While SELA was issuing this declaration, the Nonaligned 
Movement's 11th Foreign Ministers Conference demanded an end to 
the U.S. blockade of Cuba and asked Washington to stop 
committing acts contrary to the spirit of being a good neighbor. 
In addition, SELA asked for the return of Guantanamo Naval Base. 
  These governmental and popular rejections of U.S. harassment 
of Cuba echo two resolutions that were approved two years in a 
row by the UN General Assembly in 1992 and 1993. As of today, 
however, the U.S. Government has failed to heed the letter and 
spirit of these resolutions. The fact that the White House 
appears to be ignoring international pronouncements against the 
blockade does not detract from the importance or the value of 
these declarations. On the contrary, these actions are simply 
proof of the stubbornness of a nation that is ignoring a growing 
international trend. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-33870 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat113_b_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-113 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  10 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

