<F P=100> Barbados </F>
<F P=101> Dominican Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Border Crossing for Food, Medicine Banned </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Border Crossing for Food, Medicine Banned </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1106025794 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 0102 GMT 11 Jun 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1106025794 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Santo Domingo, 10 Jun (NOTIMEX) -- Due to several 
violent incidents on the Haitian border, today, Dominican 
Republic authorities suspended the crossing of Haitians into the 
Dominican Republic to seek food and medicine. 
  Army sources told the international press that the crossing 
of Haitians to purchase food and medicine was suspended on 
Friday after small groups were allowed to cross early in the day. 
  The crossing of people carrying food and medicine into Haiti 
continues to be restricted on the border after a Dominican 
soldier, posted in Dajabon in northern Dominican Republic, had 
his rifles snatched away from him on Thursday, provincial 
governor Abilio Escoto explained. 
  Local authorities said that in similar incidents, Haitians 
hurled stones at soldiers who patrol the common border. None of 
the attacks have been repelled up to now. 
  The UN Security Council augmented the economic embargo 
against Haiti on 21 May to force the coupist military officers 
who overthrew Jean Bertrand Aristide in 1991 to abandon power. 
  The Dominican Republic shares with Haiti the Caribbean 
island 
of Hispaniola and the common border is patrolled by 
approximately 15,000 Dominican soldiers under the observation of 
a U.S. mission that analyzes local Army needs to comply with the 
UN mandate. President Joaquin Balaguer was against sanctions on 
Haiti, but he promised to comply with them. 
  On Thursday, the president announced that according to a 
list 
sent by the United Nations, the sale of food and medicine to 
Haitians is to be allowed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

