<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Salinas Orders Army To Maintain Chiapas Cease-Fire </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Salinas Orders Army To Maintain Chiapas Cease-Fire </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1306030694 Paris AFP in Spanish 0145 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1306030694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 12 Jun (AFP) -- On 12 June, Mexican 
President Carlos Salinas de Gortari ordered the National Defense 
Secretariat to maintain a "unilateral cease-fire" in the 
conflict in the southern State of Chiapas, where the Zapatist 
National Liberation Army [EZLN] rejected official proposals to 
reach peace agreements. 
  A communique issued by the Presidency of the republic stated 
that Salinas ordered the Mexican Army to maintain the cease-fire 
and continue to patrol the country's southern border to prevent 
any gunrunning. 
  On 11 June, the EZLN, which staged an armed rebellion in 
January, rejected the government's offers and virtually broke 
off the negotiations by summoning a National Democratic 
Congress, whose goal, among others, is reportedly to establish a 
provisional government. 
  "Attentive to the indeclinable determination of the 
government of the republic to preserve peace and guarantee the 
economic and political development of the region, which is 
immersed in a conflict, the president ordered various 
institution to continue implementing programs and executing 
actions that were previously agreed upon," the document added. 
  Salinas also ordered Peace Commissioner Manuel Camacho Solis 
to continue efforts to find a political and negotiated solution 
to the conflict in Chiapas. The EZLN rejected government 
proposals but also decided to maintain a unilateral cease-fire 
and to continue seeking a solution to the "war" in Chiapas. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

