<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Fabian Dubal] </F>
  [Text] Cartagena de Indias, Colombia (NA) -- President 
Carlos Menem will participate in the Fourth Ibero-American Heads 
of State and Government Summit where "crucial issues of today's 
world" will be discussed. 
  Menem arrived at the local airport at 1915 (2115 Argentine 
time) [0015 GMT 14 June]. After a brief contact with 
journalists, he headed for the Hilton Hotel where he will stay 
together with the other heads of state attending the meeting. 
  Menem reiterated that he is willing to meet Cuban leader 
Fidel Castro "if he" asks for a meeting. 
  Regarding the Cuban situation Menem said "for years 
Argentina 
respected the blockade" imposed by the United States. The 
Argentine president made clear, however, that Argentina "has 
good relations" with the island and is "constantly monitoring" 
the situation. 
  "The possibilities for integration are enormous if Cuba 
becomes democratic," Menem stressed. 
  The Argentine president was accompanied by Foreign Minister 
Guido Di Tella. 
  Menem also mentioned the world soccer tournament and 
reiterated that the championship will be won by either 
Argentina, Germany, Brazil, Colombia, or Italy. 

</TEXT>

