<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaffirms Rejection of Blockade </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reaffirms Rejection of Blockade </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1406022394 Havana Radio Havana Cuba in Spanish 0000 GMT 14 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1406022394 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Havana Cuba </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Evening Information Review" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Mexican President Carlos Salinas de Gortari, during 
a news conference in Havana, has reaffirmed his opposition to 
the U.S. blockade against Cuba, a country toward which he will 
always promote solidarity and respect. 
  Shortly before concluding his brief visit to the Cuban 
capital, Salinas de Gortari told the local and foreign media 
that, in his talks with his counterpart Fidel Castro, he 
discussed political and economic issues, including trade and 
investments by private Mexican citizens in the island. 
  In this regard, he confirmed an important investment by a 
Mexican company in the Cuban telephone industry as well as the 
preference that will be granted to the import of Cuban products 
such as textile products, tiles, and prefabricated houses. 
  As for the Fourth Ibero-American summit that will start on 
Tuesday, the Mexican president said he will attend it convinced 
that specific results will be achieved in the areas of trade and 
integration. He added that summits have shown their value as 
formidable political forums to collectively discuss issues that 
are common to all peoples of the region. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

