<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   10 Officially Register as Presidential Candidates </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    10 Officially Register as Presidential Candidates </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1306200994 Sao Paulo AGENCIA ESTADO in Portuguese 2223 GMT 
10 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY1306200994 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo AGENCIA ESTADO </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Rosa Costa] </F>
  [Text] Brasilia, 10 Jun (AE) -- Ten people have registered 
at the Superior Electoral Court (TSE) as presidential 
candidates. The deadline for coalitions and parties to file 
their respective petitions expired at 1900 today. The TSE will 
review the documents submitted by the presidential hopefuls 
before officially approving their candidacies. The electoral 
timetable provides that the TSE will have to rule on petitions 
and appeals by 20 July. 
  The candidates are: Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva (PT) [Workers 
Party], Fernando Henrique Cardoso (PSDB) [Brazilian Social 
Democracy Party], Orestes Quercia (PMDB) [Brazilian Democratic 
Movement Party], Leonel Brizola (PDT) [Democratic Labor Party], 
Esperidiao Amin (PPR) [Popular Renewal Party], Flavio Rocha (PL) 
[Liberal Party], Eneas Carneiro (PRONA) [Party for the 
Redefinition of the National Order], Hernani Goulart Fortuna 
(PSC) [Social Christian Party], Walter Queiroz (PRN) [National 
Reconstruction Party], and Caetano Matano (PT do B) [Brazilian 
Workers Party -- Partido Trabalhista do Brasil]. They represent 
18 of the 21 parties -- most of which have formed coalitions -- 
that are qualified to nominate presidential candidates. The PP 
[Popular Party], the PRP [Progressive Republican Party], and the 
PMN [National Mobilization Party] are staying out of the race. 
  Only the PSDB and PDT candidates personally appeared before 
the TSE to submit their documents. All other candidates were 
represented by members of their parties. 
  Two petitions to register party names that are not legally 
constituted were also processed even though they do not have a 
provisional register. They are the PNSDC [National Social 
Democratic Christian Party -- Partido Nacional Social 
Democratico Cristao] and the PTRB [Brazilian Labor Renewal Party 
-- Partido Trabalhista Renovador Brasileiro]. In principle 
these petitions comply with legal provisions. They will be 
reviewed by TSE members at the beginning of next week. They 
must decide if the parties, the coalitions, and the candidates 
for president and vice president fulfill the requirements 
established by the party and electoral laws and the Constitution. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

